The following snippet fails to compile with a pretty confusing error message (at least to me):

```rust
struct Parser<'a> {
    cached: Token<'a>
}
struct Token<'a> {
    a: &'a str,
}
impl<'a> Parser<'a> {
    fn new(s: &str) -> Parser {
        Parser { cached: Token{ a: s } }
    }  
    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<&Token<'a>> {
        Some(&self.cached)
    }  
}

fn main() {
    let mut parser = Parser::new("hello");
    let mut tokens = vec![];
    while let Some(token) = parser.next() {
        tokens.push(token)
    }  
}
```

```
error[E0499]: cannot borrow `parser` as mutable more than once at a time
  --> src/main.rs:36:29
   |
36 |     while let Some(token) = parser.next() {
   |                             ^^^^^^
   |                             |
   |                             second mutable borrow occurs here
   |                             first mutable borrow occurs here
...
39 | }
   | - first borrow ends here
```

Ideally, the second mutable borrow would point to `tokens.push(token)`, which is actually the source of the problem.

(Note that replacing `while let` with `if let` or replacing `tokens.push(token)` with `tokens.push(token.clone())` lets this example compile successfully).

This happens in both the latest Rust stable (1.19) and the latest nightly.
